}}
A '''hysterotomy''' is an incision in the [[uterus]], and is performed during a [[caesarean section]]. Hysterotomies are also performed during [[fetal surgery]], and various gynaecological procedures.{{Citation needed|date=October 2018}}

In fetal surgery, without inhibition of uterine contractions, [[premature labor]] is a complication that occurs in 100% of hysterotomy cases.<ref>{{Cite journal| doi = 10.1016/S0022-5223(98)70400-3| last1 = Assad | first1 = R. S.| last2 = Hanley | first2 = F. L.| title = Artificial placenta--a need for fetal surgery?| journal = The Journal of Thoracic and Cardiovascular Surgery| volume = 115| issue = 5| pages = 1021–1022| year = 1998| pmid = 9605070}} {{cite web |url=http://jtcs.ctsnetjournals.org/cgi/content/full/115/5/1021 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-11-28 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120721214244/http://jtcs.ctsnetjournals.org/cgi/content/full/115/5/1021 |archivedate=2012-07-21 |df= }}</ref> It can be inhibited by [[tocolytic]]s.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Sutton LN |title=Fetal surgery for neural tube defects |journal=Best Pract Res Clin Obstet Gynaecol |volume=22 |issue=1 |pages=175–88 |date=February 2008 |pmid=17714997 |pmc=2293328 |doi=10.1016/j.bpobgyn.2007.07.004 |url=}}</ref>

