{{Use South African English|date=July 2017}}
'''Suna Venter''' was a South African current affairs journalist, fiction writer, and senior [[radio producer]] at the [[South African Broadcasting Corporation]] (SABC). She was one of a group of eight journalists at the SABC that were suspended in 2016 for objecting to the editorial policies implemented by SABC COO [[Hlaudi Motsoeneng]] known as the [[SABC8]].
Most notably the policy by the SABC of refusing to air protest footage. The policy was reversed following a parliamentary enquiry.<ref name="tl">{{Cite web|url=https://www.timeslive.co.za/news/2017-06-30-sabc8-journo-suna-venter-dies-of-broken-heart|title=SABC8 journo Suna Venter dies of 'broken heart'|last=MAILOVICH|first=CLAUDI|date=30 June 2017|website=Timeslive|access-date=5 July 2017}}</ref>
Following their suspension the journalists including Venter were the victims of numerous death threats, home break-ins and other forms of intimidation to get them to drop a Constitutional Court case against the SABC.<ref name="tl2016">{{Cite web|url=https://www.timeslive.co.za/sunday-times/news/2016-09-18-death-threats-spook-sabc-staffers|title=Death threats spook SABC staffers|last=HOFSTATTER|first=STEPHAN|date=18 September 2016|website=Timeslive|access-date=5 July 2017}}</ref><ref name="iol">{{Cite web |url=http://www.iol.co.za/news/politics/sabc-8-journalist-suna-venter-dies-from-broken-heart-syndrome-10056165|title=SABC 8 journalist Suna Venter dies from 'Broken Heart Syndrome'|date=29 June 2017|website=iol|access-date=5 July 2017}}</ref>
==Death== On 29 June 2017, Venter was found dead in her home in Kelland, Johannesburg. She was 32 years old. Her death is believed to have resulted from stress induced [[cardiomyopathy]] caused by the intimidation attempts against her following her and her colleagues' criticism of Motsoeneng's policies.<ref name="hp">{{Cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.za/2017/06/29/sabc-8-journalist-suna-venter-dead-at-32_a_23008060|title=SABC-8 Journalist Suna Venter Dead At 32|last=Etheridge|first=Jenna|date=29 June 2017|website=Huffington Post|access-date=5 July 2017}}</ref>
The [[Inkatha Freedom Party]] made a statement following her death that she "was a hero of all times."<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ewn.co.za/2017/07/01/suna-venter-was-a-hero|title=SUNA VENTER WAS A HERO|last=Phakgadi|first=Pelane|date=1 July 2017|website=ewn.com|access-date=5 July 2017}}</ref> Others condolences came from included those from South African journalists as well as the Ahmed Kathrada Foundation,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.iol.co.za/news/politics/kathrada-foundation-salutes-suna-venter-slams-blf-threats-10094613|title=Kathrada Foundation salutes Suna Venter, slams BLF threats|access-date=9 July 2017}}</ref> and [[Right2Know]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.politicsweb.co.za/politics/blf-also-gupta-cronies--r2k|title=BLF also Gupta cronies|website=politicsweb.co.za|access-date=9 July 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.iol.co.za/dailynews/tributes-flow-for-a-jewel---sabc-journalist-suna-venter-10139199|title=Tributes flow for ‘a jewel’|access-date=9 July 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/friends-colleagues-bid-farewell-to-brave-fiesty-suna-venter-20170706|title=Friends, colleagues bid farewell to 'brave, fiesty' Suna Venter|work=News24|access-date=9 July 2017}}</ref>
Suna was survived by her mother Christa, father Philip, sister Tessa, and brother Wilhelm. The SAPS is investigating her death, but the investigating officer told the family that her death was caused by heart failure.
