[[Admiral]] '''Sir William Garnham Luard''' [[Order of the Bath|KCB]] (7 April 1820 – 19 May 1910) was a leading British naval figure during the latter half of the 19th century.<ref>The Illustrated Naval and Military Magazine, Volume V, W.H. Allen & co, 1886</ref>

==Naval career==
Born in 1820, he was the eldest son of a local magistrate, William Wright Luard J.P., D.L. of Witham Lodge,<ref>see Men of Bad Character: the Witham Fires of the 1820s by Janet Gyford</ref> [[Witham]], Essex (formerly of [[Hatfield Peverel Priory]]) and Anne Garnham, only child of Thomas Garnham of Felsham Hall, Suffolk.<ref name=burke>[https://books.google.com/books?id=Ni4BAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA909&lpg=PA909&dq=%22William+Luard%22&source=bl&ots=n4q6VCywCN&sig=CbI5y7amBhIxcAcQr9-FElPLW1I&hl=en&ei=5Sn8S8-8KpvMNJmugYkC&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1&ved=0CBMQ6AEwADgK#v=onepage&q=%22William%20Luard%22&f=false A Genealogical and Heraldic Dictionary of the Landed Gentry of Great Britain, Volume 2 By Sir Bernard Burke, p. 909]</ref> The Luards were a prominent family of Protestant [[Huguenot]] merchants who had fled to England in the late 17th century as part of the mass exodus of Huguenots from France to England that followed the [[Edict of Fontainebleau|1685 revocation]] of the [[Edict of Nantes]].<ref name=burke/>

Luard entered the Royal Naval College (formerly the [[Royal Naval Academy]]) at [[Portsmouth]] at the age of 13 and later studied at Portsmouth Naval College. He served extensively and saw action in the South China Sea, for which he was recognized in dispatches and decorated for gallantry and bravery several times including being named Companion of the [[Order of the Bath]] (CB).<ref name=odnb>[http://www.oxforddnb.com/index/101034617 Oxford Dictionary of National Biography]</ref>

After a distinguished career as a naval officer, including as captain and commander of {{HMS|Formidable|1825|6}} and [[HMS Waterloo (1833)|HMS ''Conqueror'']], he served as superintendent of the [[Sheerness Dockyard]] and the [[Malta Dockyard]]. From 1882 to 1885, he was [[President]] of the [[Royal Naval College, Greenwich]].<ref name=odnb/>

He was awarded the Burmese War Medal for dispersing the pirates of Chin-a-poo and received the Medal of the Legion of Honour, 4th Class, from Emperor [[Napoleon III]]. He was promoted [[Rear-Admiral (Royal Navy)|Rear-Admiral]] in 1875, [[Vice-Admiral (Royal Navy)|Vice-Admiral]] on 15 June 1879,<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=24734|page=3967|date=17 June 1879}}</ref> and [[Admiral (Royal Navy)|Admiral]] in 1885.<ref name=odnb/> 

Luard was advanced to [[Order of the Bath|KCB]] by [[Queen Victoria]] in 1897, during her diamond jubilee year.<ref name=odnb/>

Luard married Charlotte Du Cane (an anglicization of the original French surname 'Du Quesne') in 1858. She was from another French Huguenot family (see [[Jean Du Quesne, the elder]] and descendants), with landed estates at [[Braxted Park]] and [[Coggeshall]].<ref>[http://worldroots.com/brigitte/famous/j/jeanduquesnedesc.htm Worldroots.com<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060314173004/http://worldroots.com/brigitte/famous/j/jeanduquesnedesc.htm |date=14 March 2006 }}</ref><ref>The English 'Du Quesnes' were from a branch of the family of the famous French [[Admiral]] [[Abraham Duquesne]], Marquis du Bouchet — see [[Jean Du Quesne, the elder]]</ref> Admiral and Lady Luard had 11 children.<ref name=odnb/>

A staunch [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal]] and supporter of Prime Minister [[William Gladstone]], Luard retired to his estate in Essex<ref>The Lodge, Witham, Essex</ref> where he served as a [[Justice of the Peace]] and as an active member of the court of Quarter Sessions. He died in 1910 as a result of injuries sustained in a carriage accident.<ref name=odnb/>

